shared_text:
Riverview Intermediate Unit #6
September 9 at 10:18 AM ·

Guest Teacher Training at RIU6 – Substitutes needed for RIU6 Region Schools

September 15 @ RIU6 from 8-3pm.

If you have a College Degree, an Emergency Teaching Permit can be issued for you to do day to day subbing in our schools as much or as little as needed. This training is a small preparatory program with some virtual videos, lots of paperwork, a few key special education topics, and a $25 processing fee, and you can get your emergency teaching permit to substitute in our schools and make some money on off days or every day as our schools are desperate. Email mlaverde@riu6.org or call 814-297-5103.



Future Training Days:

9/15/20, 11/10/20, 1/26/21, 3/30/21

9/7/21, 11/9/21, 1/25/22, 3/29/22

Cranberry Area School District continues to experience problems with the district phone system. We anticipate having service restored towards the end of the week of September 7th. We understand this is a huge inconvenience and are working to restore telephone service as soon as possible. We have access to emergency lines to call out only.

Please rely on emailing us if you need to communicate with anyone in the district. Email addresses can be found at www.cranberrysd.org

Thank you for your patience while we work to restore telephone service.

Pennsylvania Department of Human Services
May 15 at 8:00 AM ·

🚨 PARENTS: A new program is available to help feed school-aged children who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals through the National School Lunch Program (NSLP). Families who have experienced a job loss or decreased wages due to #COVID19 can still apply for NSLP to receive this benefit. Through the Pandemic Electronic Benefits Transfer (P-EBT) program, you may be eligible for additional temporary benefits.

❓ Get more information at bit.ly/PASNAPPBET.
💻 Apply online at www.compass.state.pa.us.

Note: P-EBT will not affect your regular SNAP or TANF benefits.

Berries, here is a way to support your community!

The residents at Oakwood Heights Nursing Home are currently unable to receive visitors due to Covid-19. Many are used to seeing family on a regular basis. The staff continue to work hard providing for daily needs and extending tender loving care to these precious residents. We’ve been asked to help spread some cheer through notes, cards, drawings, and words of encouragement.

Cards for residents and/or staff may be sent to:
Oakwood Heights
c/o Rays of Sunshine
10 Vo-Tech Dr.
Oil City, PA 16301

Thank you!

post_text:
This afternoon, Governor Wolf announced that all schools in the commonwealth will remain closed through at least April 6 as a result of the COVID-19 response efforts. The closure order could be extended beyond April 6 if necessary to save lives and stop the spread of COVID-19.

Under the new timeline, school buildings would reopen to staff on April 7 for two days to allow school administrators, teachers and other staff time to prepare classrooms, set up cafeterias, schedule transportation and arrange other business operations. Students would return to school on April 9, unless extending the closure is needed in response to the situation with the virus at that time. Thank you

CranNews JPub is with Melissa Hoover Redfield.
March 12 at 8:39 PM ·

JOURNALISM STUDENTS AT CHS AWARDED FOR THEIR WORK

Journalism students at Cranberry High School place in several categories at the Pennsylvania NewsMedia Association’s (PNA) Keystone Press Awards.

In the Ongoing News Coverage category, students were awarded 1st place. Those students included Joe Gunn, Jenna Seigworth, Dylan Lu, Amber Holt, and Hannah Niederriter.

Taking 3rd place in the Video Story category were students Jillian Plummer, Hunter Redfield, and Jacob Umstead.

Two students earned awards in the News Photo category: Cara Andres won 2nd place and Gabe Dresbach won 3rd.

Winning 3 awards in photography this year is junior Ava Fischer. She won 1st place in the Feature Photo category, 2nd place in the Sports Photo category, and 2nd place in the Photo Story category.

*Photo Caption:
Back row: Gabe Dresbach, Dylan Lu, Joe Gunn, Cara Andres, Jillian Plummer, Hunter Redfield, Jacob Umstead; Front Row: Hannah Niederriter, Amber Holt, Ava Fischer, Jenna Seigworth

Cranberry VEX IQ Team Advances to World's

Cranberry High School's junior high group called "Team McQueens" qualified for World's today by winning the Middle School Excellence Award at Western PA VEX IQ States held at Clarion University.

The team consists of 8th graders (pictured from left to right in the photograph) Rylee Coe, Jordan Montgomery, Alaina Olson, and Maria Galletta.

"Team McQueens" will travel to World's held in Louisville, Kentucky this April.

We are 'Berry' proud!

post_text: Cranberry students, Morgan Stover and Nick Richar, competing for the Oil City High School Swim Team have qualified for the PIAA State Swim Competition. Morgan will be competing in the 400 free relay and the 200 free relay with her teammates from Oil City. Morgan also captured a 6th place individual medal in the 100 breaststroke. Nick will be competing in the 400 freestyle relay and the 200 free relay with his Oil City teammates. Nick also achieved a 5th place individual medal in the 100 backstroke. Great job Morgan and Nick, and all the swimmers from OC who qualified for the state meet! Go Berries!! Go OC!!

post_text: This past snowy weekend PMEA Region II held its choral festival in Corry, PA. Five Cranberry students, Rachel, Michael, Joe, Trevor, and Trey earned their way to be invited to perform (Eben also earned his way to perform but had another commitment). During the festival, through auditions, Trey earned a 10th seat, Michael earned a 6th seat, and Trevor earned a 4th seat. By placing in the 4th seat Trevor will now move on to perform at the state level choral concert in the Poconos. Great job Trevor! Congratulations on this accomplishment! All our talented singers did a wonderful job! Thank you, Mr. Yoder, for all your work in preparing these students to perform. Go Berries!

CranNews JPub
February 11 at 10:37 AM ·

Athlete of the week: Carter Stanley
Written by Cara Andres
Photography by Cassidy Miller

This week’s athlete of the week is Carter Stanley.

Being a great role model and how he conducts himself on and off the mat are two reasons why Coach Wenner nominated Carter as athlete of the week.

Stanley wrestles in the Cranberry-Oil City co-op wrestling team and has a 15-1 record.

An Armstrong Winter Classic Champion, Stanley is also the Mid-Winter Mayhem runner up.

“Carter is an extremely hard worker and has enjoyed much success due to his work ethic,” said Head Coach Dustin Wenner.

Stanley is also involved in acapella choir and broadcasting club at Oil City High School.

February 4 at 3:47 PM ·

Athlete of the Week: Matt McQuaide
Written by Zoe Albert | 1/31/20
Photograph by Ava Fischer

This week’s Athlete of the Week is basketball player Matt McQuaide.

Matt is a senior at Cranberry and this is his fourth year participating on the basketball team.

He helped his team accomplish two recent victories against Union and Redbank, contributing 40 points and 17 rebounds in the game against Redbank alone.

According to Coach Irwin, Matt “has consistently set a positive example both on and off the court throughout the season.”

Along with basketball, Matt enjoys going on annual mission trips, the most recent one being to Jamaica, and he enjoys watching sports and hanging out with his friends.

post_text: District chorus 2020 was held at United High High School last week in Armagh, Pennsylvania. Nine hard-working, talented singers from Cranberry qualified to attend. CranNews JPub
December 20, 2019 at 5:00 PM ·

Annual Santa Shop
By Brooke Whitling | 12/17/19

On Monday, December 16th, Cranberry Jr./Sr. High School hosted its annual Santa Shop.

Designed to allow select students the opportunity to give back to family members, the event entered its 8th year.

“We created this in an effort to spread cheer in school before students go home on Christmas break,” Paula Turk, one of the event’s organizers, stated of the Shop’s original purpose.

Students invited to participate shop from items donated by Cranberry staff and community members. This year, the event allowed fifty-three students to select items for their loved ones.

Turk says that she gets many grateful emails from families, thanking her for presenting the students with this opportunity.

The student feedback is also extremely positive, explains Turk, “They are so full of smiles and happiness on that day, and it makes the entire preparation process worth it.”

shared_text:
CranNews JPub
December 7, 2019 at 12:33 AM ·

Girls Coding at Cranberry
By Nick Richar

This year Cranberry has added a brand new club, Girls Who Code.

The club is run by Mr. Colin Milne, the school librarian.

When asked about Girls Who Code, Milne explained, “This club is a national club. It focuses on getting females involved with coding.”

He also made notice that anyone can join this club, it is just more girl centered, but the coding lessons are the same regardless of gender.

“I want everyone to have an opportunity,” he stated.

He mentioned that most of the workers in the coding and software designing fields are men, which is why the club is more focused around girls.

Milne finished the interview with a positive outlook on the future of the club. He plans on getting more girls involved with coding so that it balances the ratio of both men and women in the coding field.

CranNews JPub
October 17, 2019 at 3:39 PM ·

White Cane Day
Written by Ady Carter and Natalie Sandrock
Photography by Cara Andres

The Venango County Association for the Blind came to Cranberry High School on Tuesday, October 15th to share and do an interactive lesson with the junior class on White Cane Day.

Black canes used to cause problems because they weren’t easily visible. The white canes came about in the 1930s. Then, in 1964, the national day was organized and signed by Lyndon B. Johnson.

The association taught the students how to properly assist the blind. The tips they were given included making sure to ask before they try to assist someone, as not everyone may want or need help, and to remember to use verbal cues.

Students were also told about challenges the blind have locally. These challenges include having to wait months to learn how to properly use a cane, along with something such as a grocery store being rearranged. To a sighted person, this is mildly disruptive, but this can be very significant to the blind.

Written by Nick Richar

Ava Ferringer is our new Athlete of the week. She has been in the spotlight recently with her performances in volleyball.

Ferringer helped the team with a 2-1 record for the week plus an 8-1 record overall. Ava lead the team in kills each of the three games this week with 9, all while maintaining a 3.9 GPA.

Ava will back on the court tonight for Senior Night. JV starts at 6 with Senior night and Varsity to follow.

Written by Zoe Albert

This week’s Athlete of the Week is Cameron Russell.

When asked how it felt to receive this honor, Russell responded, “Feels good, feels rewarding, really proud of myself.”

Russell plays for the Co-Op Oil City Oilers Football team and has already begun an extremely fruitful season with 9.5 sacks, 74 carries, 640 rushing yards, 6 touchdowns, and 5.5 tackles.

Russell also competes with the basketball team, the track and field team, and the wrestling team.

Receiving this award proves to be especially motivational for Russell.

He has stated that he plans to continue to work hard and hopefully motivate others to do so as well.

Athlete of the Week: Matt Woolcock
By Brooke Whitling and Gabe Dresbach

Leading by example and attending every practice are just two reasons Coach Siverling gave when speaking of the newest student of the week.

In recent weeks, Woolcock won 1st place at a dual meet with North Clarion and Brockway, and 2nd place overall at the Commodore Perry invitational.

“He is hard working, very goal oriented, and is always motivated; he‘s just a very kind person in general,” says Oliver, assistant boys cross country coach.

When asked how it feels to be the Athlete of the Week, Woolcock said, “It feels good. I really like the recognition.”

Receiving this honor, Woolcock hopes it encourages him to do well and that it inspires others to keep up the hard work.

shared_text:
Richard Sayer/Photojournalism Page
September 17, 2019 at 10:15 PM ·

Into the gym tonight for some volleyball action. Years ago I would photograph 2-5 matches a week. I joked with Cranberry principal Rit Smith tonight when i got into the gym, "it's like riding a bike right?" Then I lifted my camera and made one frame, following the action I made 4 more when the volley ended. My fifth frame was first picture here. That was the only one I looked at before smiling and looking at Rit and saying "I still got it!"
Normally I struggle to find a groove in a match but today I just got on it right away. Felt good. Makes me want to do more, but I'm going on vacation next week so when i get back I'm sure it will be back to struggling at first. But I love my job.

By Anna Moore

Athlete of the Week goes to one of the many hard working individuals at Cranberry High School, junior Kalynne Ziegler.

shared_text:
CranNews JPub is with Jessica Guth.
September 11, 2019 at 11:17 AM ·

Walk to School Day
Written by Jacob Umstead and Hunter Redfield

Several students and staff participated in “Walk to School” day, an annual event at Cranberry High School.

Hosted by the CRANA club, “Walk to School” day is a great opportunity for students to get extra exercise to start their day.

Students were dropped off at the intersection of Education drive and Big Egypt road and walked up the school’s scenic back drive.

During the walk, the back drive was blocked off from traffic to provide safety for students and staff.

CRANA club members unloaded backpacks from the buses then students picked them up after the walk before entering the school. Club members also handed out water bottles to all participants.

The main focus for “Walk to School” day is to encourage students to be more active not only during school, but outside of school as well.

Cran News Staff | 8/30/19

Andrea Ziegler, an 11th grader, is the first recognized this year in Cranberry’s new Athlete of the Week program created by vice-principal Mr. Deemer and Athletic Director Mr. Earp.

Based on her average scores over the first four golf matches, Andrea is currently third in Cranberry’s golf league.

Notably, she has the best average among Cranberry’s golfers.

Last golf season, Andrea averaged a 52 which lead to her going to PIAA Girls Golf Districts.

In addition to golfing, Andrea is in bowling and a member of Science club, Conservation club, NHS, and Ignite.

August 30, 2019 at 3:44 PM ·

Cranberry’s Athlete of the Week: Andrea Ziegler
Cran News Staff | 8/30/19

Andrea Ziegler, an 11th grader, is the first recognized this year in Cranberry’s new Athlete of the Week program created by vice-principal Mr. Deemer and Athletic Director Mr. Earp.

Based on her average scores over the first four golf matches, Andrea is currently third in Cranberry’s golf league.

Notably, she has the best average among Cranberry’s golfers.

Last golf season, Andrea averaged a 52 which lead to her going to PIAA Girls Golf Districts.

In addition to golfing, Andrea is in bowling and a member of Science club, Conservation club, NHS, and Ignite.

Photo:
Athletic Director, Brad Earp, presenting 11th grader Andrea Ziegler with a t-shirt, recognizing her for being this week’s Athlete of the Week (photo taken by Ava Fischer)

Schedule Pick-up

Schedules for students in grades 8 - 12 will be uploaded to the portals on Wednesday, August 14. Hard copies of schedules along with other back to school information that needs to be completed and returned will be in the student’s homeroom on the first day of school. Mr. Godinich will be available for questions regarding schedules for grades 10 - 12 starting on August 14. Mrs. Corbett will be available for questions regarding schedules for grades 8 - 9 starting on August 19.

Schedules for grade 7 and new students to the district will be distributed at orientation.

Chromebooks - Grades 9-12

Chromebooks will be issued to students during the first week of school. Forms for insurance will be emailed/mailed to parents. Please send forms with your child noting if you would or would not like insurance. If you would like insurance, please also include payment with checks made out to CHS.

CranNews JPub
April 15, 2019 at 12:58 PM ·

FEATHERS FLYING IN THIRD GRADE
By: Carly Wice and Rachael McCauley - Cran News Reporters
4-15-19

Mrs. Findley´s third grade class at Cranberry Elementary recently hatched a few different breeds of chickens. The students hatched Ameraucana, Golden Polish Laced, and Silver Polish Laced chicks.

Nine chicks hatched all together and the class has not yet determined the gender of all of the chicks. Mrs. Findley has been teaching the children how to determine the sex of the chicks based on their rows of feathers and the curves of their beaks.

This has been Mrs. Findley´s sixteenth year hatching eggs with her students, and she looks forward to hatching different breeds of birds in future years.

April 10, 2019 at 1:23 PM ·

THE PUPPY POST: A COMMUNITY PARTNERSHIP
Crannews Staff

Journalism tells stories and speaks for those who sometimes don't have a voice. In searching for a community partnership, our Journalism class decided to join with the efforts of our local Humane Society in Seneca, PA.

We think it is important to promote dogs who are surrendered for various reasons: neglect, surrender, or stray, sometimes found wandering around in terrible condition.

The Humane Society takes them in, helps them heal, and finds forever homes for these animals.

Each Wednesday, a student team of journalists goes to the shelter to take pictures and get information on the dogs. The information is then transferred to the "Puppy Post" in hopes that more people will see these animals.

Visit our page to see the dogs who need a home, and, please, continue to adopt, not shop!

https://sites.google.com/cranberrysd.org/cranberry-chronicles/puppy-post

STUDENTS COMPETE IN CURRENT EVENTS
By Crannews Staff | Photography by Gayle Mitchell | 4/8/2019

Students in the gifted program at Cranberry High School competed today in the Current Events challenge.

The IU6 hosted the event which included schools in both Clarion and Venango counties.

Students in the 7th-8th grade division earned first place and included Jonah Dean, Connor Miller, Alaina Olson, and Alexis Dehner.

Winning third place in the 11th-12th grade division included students Dylan Lu, Trevor Olson, Maria Anderson, and Hannah Niederritier. Of note, all Cranberry students competing in this division were in grades 9 or 10, so they were playing up.

CranNews JPub
March 27, 2019 at 2:18 PM ·

Duck, duck....sorry, no goose
CranNews Staff

Cranberry Elementary School has a live cam set up for students to watch duck eggs hatch! This is a school-wide event and teachers have the option of talking about it in their classes.

Eggs started incubation on March 4th and they are expected to hatch April 1st. Sources say that they are expecting at least 30 eggs to make it. Once the ducklings hatch, staff members will be taking them home.

Watch the live cam here: http://inet.cranberrysd.org/intranet/duckcam.html
*You will need Flash to be able to watch it. Also, if you are outside of our network, you may not be able to watch it. We are troubleshooting this for you.

BECOME A GUEST TEACHER
Riverview Intermediate Unit Emergency Substitute Teacher Consortium is interested in finding qualified personnel as guest teachers to replace regular classroom teachers during training sessions and/or leave time for the 2018-2019 school year.

To be considered you need to have:
- Proof of bachelors degree from an accredited U.S. college or university
- Current Act 34, Act 114 (fingerprinting) and Act 151 Clearances Required

Contact Christine Merryman, Human Resources & Personnel Manager, Riverview Intermediate Unit, 814-226-7103 x 5116 so that you can be sent an application packet. Applications will be accepted no later than March 29, 2019, following which you will be registered for the training to be held April 11, 2019 at the Riverview Intermediate Unit Headquarters Building. The cost of the program is $25 payable upon registration. EOE.
Those who successfully complete the training sessions will be substitutes in the various public school districts, who are members of the RIU Emergency Substitute Teacher Consortium and are equal opportunity employers.

post_text: Nick Richar, a Cranberry Berry swimming in our coop with Oil City is going to states as part of the relay team!! Great job to Nick and the rest of the swim team!
shared_text:
Oil City High School Swim Team
March 4, 2019 at 9:02 PM ·

It’s official - the Oilers have their first male PIAA relay since 1998. Nick Richar, Tom Schneider, Bob Wenner and Zach Malek qualified in both freestyle relays and broke the team record in the 400 relay. Tom qualified for the PIAA meet in the 500 freestyle as well, bringing the Oilers the first male individual qualifier since 2014. Stay tuned for the updates to the top 10 list.

Cranberry Student Earns 2nd in Academic Bowl
By CranNews

One of our very own journalists, Dylan Lu, participated in the Academic Bowl on February 5th at the IU6.

For those unaware, the Academic Bowl is more challenging, as far as the questions, than the Academic Challenge that students take part in earlier in the year.

Competing against students in grades 9-12 from 6 different schools, Dylan won 2nd place as an individual scorer!

Way to go Dylan!

post_text: A group of Cranberry students joined the Pennsylvania Fish Commission on the cold morning of January 28, 2019, to help net steelhead trout from tributaries of Lake Erie. The steelhead were given antibiotics, and eggs and sperm were collected to help ensure future generations of steelhead in Lake Erie. Everyone had a great time and learned a lot about steelhead trout conservation. Education in action!

post_text:
S.E.I. AWARD WINNERS ANNOUNCED

Three Cranberry students were honored with SEI (Service, Effort, and Initiative) Awards at the Lions’ Club meeting on Monday, January 21, 2019. The biannual award recognizes three seventh and/or eighth grade students that demonstrate exemplary service, effort, and initiative, not only in their school but also in the community. The winners were nominated and selected by their teachers and school counselor. Lori Corbett, Cranberry High School counselor, announced the winners at the dinner. Each winner received a certificate, gift card, and numerous other gifts from the Cranberry Lions Club.

The winners were (from left on picture): Kyle Bechtel, Grade 8, son of Jennifer and Timothy Bechtel of Emlenton; Mackenzie Karnes, Grade 8, daughter of Jennifer and Chad Stover of Cranberry; and Jordan Montgomery, Grade 7, daughter of Tiffany and Joshua Montgomery of Seneca. Also pictured is Cranberry Lion, Larry Walker.

Great Job!!

Cranberry students dominated the recent Propaganda Tournament at IU6!! The Propaganda Tournament is an event requiring students to recognize and identify 60 different language techniques used to manipulate audiences. Students are presented with advertisements or statements and must identify which particular type of propaganda is being utilized.

Results:
First Place 11/12 Division: Dylan Lu, Maria Anderson, Hannah Niederriter, and Trevor Olson

First Place 9/10 Division: Maddy Bunyak, Noel Bunyak, Jeremy Hacherl, and Brooke Whitling

Second Place 7/8 Division: Connor Miller, Ady Carter, Jonah Dean, Alaina Olson

Recognition for overall high points in their divisions:
Maria Anderson- 1st place - 11/12
Trevor Olson - 2nd place 11/12
Dylan Lu- 3rd place 11/12
Brooke Whitling - 2nd place 9/10
Jeremy Hacherl - 3rd place 9/10
Jonah Dean-2nd place 7/8
